Service A calls Service B. Suddenly Service B becomes very slow. What will happen to Service A and how will you prevent cascading failures?


“When Service B becomes slow, threads
 in Service A get blocked waiting for responses,
 leading to thread pool exhaustion and increased latency.
 This can cascade and bring down Service A as well.
 To prevent this, I would first introduce timeouts so
 that threads don’t wait indefinitely.
 Then, I would use circuit breakers to stop calling B
  when it’s unhealthy. Bulkhead isolation ensures that calls
  to B don’t consume all resources. Controlled retries with
  exponential backoff handle transient failures, while fallbacks
  provide degraded responses to users. Additionally,
  caching and rate limiting reduce load on Service B and improve overall system resilience.”
